What's next for you is the first priority for us! With over 45 programs from associate to doctoral degrees, South University is a private institution dedicated to providing educational opportunities that spark the intellectual, social and professional development of a diverse student population.

Our 120-year story—past, present and future—is a history formed by the many individuals who have developed the education and spirit of community that have become our pledge to the students, faculty, staff, alumni and supporters of South University. Online and at our 8 locations and 2 learning sites, we take pride in our welcoming environment; one-on-one support and personalized attention that helps students define goals and identify the means to pursue them. South University, the right direction for a brighter future.


The Course Proctor will provide management and oversight of courses being broadcast into campus locations virtually. The Course Proctor will prepare the classroom for the campus-based students to receive the course virtually at the receiving campus location by. This includes setting up the technology to receive the course virtually by following the manuals and instructions provided. This will require that the Course Proctor access the Learning Management System (Brightspace) and access the live video function within the course (Kaltura). The Course Proctor will ensure that the video and audio are functioning in the classroom prior to the course beginning and will remain in the class with the students throughout the duration of the class period. At the beginning of the class, the Course Proctor will record attendance for student participation at the local campus and will send to the corresponding instructor of record at the close of the class.

Job_Description:
Mission Statement
Through the use of social and restorative justice principles, Five Keys provides traditionally underserved communities the opportunity to improve their lives through a focus on the Five Keys: EDUCATION, EMPLOYMENT, RECOVERY, FAMILY, COMMUNITY.
Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Today we are a much different social justice non-profit agency that has expanded its charter schools into 9 counties, in 24 jail locations and over 80 community learning centers. In addition to our schools, now we also run multiple homeless shelters, employment programs, programs for the unsheltered, reentry programs and housing for women suffering from immense injustice.

Title: Test Proctor
Job_Description:
PART TIME JOB.
Join our test day administration team.
IELTS is the International English Language Testing System and is a global leader in standardized English language testing, used by thousands of universities around the world, as well as for immigration to various English-speaking countries. inlingua is a local language school and we are the largest IELTS Test Center in the USA and administer the test four times a month.
We are looking for Proctors (IELTS calls them "Invigilators") to assist with a wide variety of tasks on test day. You would report to the Test Day Supervisor. This is a flexible position in that you can simply sign up for the dates you are available to work.
Invigilators are proctors who supervise the test-takers, and may also assist with checking candidate ID, checking in candidate belongings, and escorting candidates to the restroom while the test is in progress. Duties will involve test day setup, using biometrics for ID checks, ensuring security of the test, clearly communicating instructions in English, and providing smooth running of operations with a smile. Invigilators must occasionally lift and or move up to 15 pounds.

Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

Accuplacer Proctor
IntelliTec College – Pueblo, CO

We are currently seeking a Proctor for our Pueblo, CO Campus. Ideal candidates will have experience proctoring exams, a passion for helping students achieve their educational goals, and able to work a flexible work schedule.

About IntelliTec:
IntelliTec Colleges, founded in 1965, started with a simple goal to provide skilled workers to the Colorado Springs community. We shortly realized that education was more than just passing along a skill. We noticed that providing a student with an education for a specific skill set would often completely change their lives, and that inspired us to help make that change for as many students as we could. We’ve now been accomplishing our goal for over 50 years across our four campuses, three residing in Colorado and one in Albuquerque, NM. Our mission is to provide vocational education preparing our students for in-demand careers and that means preparing our students as best we can to be successful employees when they walk out the door. For our employees, the best days of the year are at each graduation ceremony when we get to see the look of accomplishment on the faces of our graduates as they walk across the stage, knowing they’re on to bigger and better things. Working at IntelliTec is about more than just paying the bills; it’s about making a difference.

Join our test day administration team.
IELTS is the International English Language Testing System and is a global leader in standardized English language testing, used by thousands of universities around the world, as well as for immigration to various English-speaking countries. inlingua is a local language school and we are the largest IELTS Test Center in the USA and administer the test four times a month.
We are looking for Proctors (IELTS calls them "Invigilators") to assist with a wide variety of tasks on test day. You would report to the Test Day Supervisor. This is a flexible position in that you can simply sign up for the dates you are available to work.

Duties will involve test day setup, using biometrics for ID checks, ensuring security of the test, clearly communicating instructions in English, and providing smooth running of operations with a smile. Invigilators must occasionally lift and or move up to 15 pounds.

IntelliTec Colleges, founded in 1965, started with a simple goal to provide skilled workers to the Colorado Springs community. We shortly realized that education was more than just passing along a skill. We noticed that providing a student with an education for a specific skill set would often completely change their lives, and that inspired us to help make that change for as many students as we could. We’ve now been accomplishing our goal for over 50 years across our four campuses, three residing in Colorado and one in Albuquerque, NM. Our mission is to provide vocational education preparing our students for in-demand careers and that means preparing our students as best we can to be successful employees when they walk out the door. For our employees, the best days of the year are at each graduation ceremony when we get to see the look of accomplishment on the faces of our graduates as they walk across the stage, knowing they’re on to bigger and better things. Working at IntelliTec is about more than just paying the bills; it’s about making a difference.

Posting Details
I. DEPARTMENT INFORMATION
Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

Mission Statement
Through the use of social and restorative justice principles, Five Keys provides traditionally underserved communities the opportunity to improve their lives through a focus on the Five Keys: EDUCATION, EMPLOYMENT, RECOVERY, FAMILY, COMMUNITY.
Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Today we are a much different social justice non-profit agency that has expanded its charter schools into 9 counties, in 24 jail locations and over 80 community learning centers. In addition to our schools, now we also run multiple homeless shelters, employment programs, programs for the unsheltered, reentry programs and housing for women suffering from immense injustice.

Posting Details
I. DEPARTMENT INFORMATION
Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

To supervise an exam as a proctor, the individual must be willing to execute the following duties listed below:







out for tests and exams.

Purpose

Provides full-time test proctoring services with Testing & Evaluation Services, which includes the UT Public Testing Center, Campus Testing Center (CTC), and Student Testing Services (STS) labs. The UT Public Testing Center provides exam proctoring for placement, proficiency, distance education, and course-specific testing for students and clients both internal and external to UT Austin, and the CTC provides exam proctoring for accommodated exams. STS administers local credit-by-exams (CBEs) for residential undergraduates and also operates an Educational Testing Services (ETS) vendor-based lab. This work supports the mission of the Testing & Evaluation Services organization at the University of Texas at Austin.

Responsibilities
Administer exams and monitor clients of UT Public Testing Center, CTC, and STS throughout duration of exams. Interact with all clients and exam sponsors professionally, including undergraduate students, students from other colleges and universities, and contractual clients. Verify client identification to ensure only approved students are testing, and ensure all required information has been completed before test begins. Regularly proctor the test sites to ensure there are no exam security violations and/or client misconduct.
Respond to unexpected occurrences with professionalism, calm demeanor, and authority. Maintain the security of testing materials before, during, and after test administrations. Maintain knowledge of exam processes for all exam sponsors. Identify process improvements for efficient exam proctoring services.
Assist with technical troubleshooting of online exam administrations. Consult with contractual exam sponsors to resolve exam administration issues. Maintain client examination files.
Provide support and backup for Testing Specialist with UT Public Testing Center to ensure compliance with exam security and administration requirements.

Required Qualifications

High school diploma and one year experience. Experience in a testing services role or working with students in a higher education program. Excellent observation skills and attention to details. Strong interpersonal and problem-solving skills. Strong organizational and administrative skills. Professional demeanor working with clients and colleagues as well as during peak periods. Ability to work cooperatively in a team environment and independently. Ability to work effectively with multiple constituencies, including a diverse student population. Enthusiasm and the ability to thrive in a high-performance environment.

Relevant education and experience may be substituted as appropriate.

Preferred Qualifications

Bachelor’s degree. More than the required experience in a professional testing services role.

$35,000 + depending on qualifications

Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

IELTS is the International English Language Testing System and is a global leader in standardized English language testing, used by thousands of universities around the world, as well as for immigration to various English-speaking countries. inlingua is a local language school and we are the largest IELTS Test Center in the USA and administer the test four times a month.

Posting Details
I. DEPARTMENT INFORMATION
Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

Through the use of social and restorative justice principles, Five Keys provides traditionally underserved communities the opportunity to improve their lives through a focus on the Five Keys: EDUCATION, EMPLOYMENT, RECOVERY, FAMILY, COMMUNITY.
Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Today we are a much different social justice non-profit agency that has expanded its charter schools into 9 counties, in 24 jail locations and over 80 community learning centers. In addition to our schools, now we also run multiple homeless shelters, employment programs, programs for the unsheltered, reentry programs and housing for women suffering from immense injustice.

Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Through the use of social and restorative justice principles, Five Keys provides traditionally underserved communities the opportunity to improve their lives through a focus on the Five Keys: EDUCATION, EMPLOYMENT, RECOVERY, FAMILY, COMMUNITY.
Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Today we are a much different social justice non-profit agency that has expanded its charter schools into 9 counties, in 24 jail locations and over 80 community learning centers. In addition to our schools, now we also run multiple homeless shelters, employment programs, programs for the unsheltered, reentry programs and housing for women suffering from immense injustice.

Join our test day administration team.
IELTS is the International English Language Testing System and is a global leader in standardized English language testing, used by thousands of universities around the world, as well as for immigration to various English-speaking countries. inlingua is a local language school and we are the largest IELTS Test Center in the USA and administer the test four times a month.
We are looking for Proctors (IELTS calls them "Invigilators") to assist with a wide variety of tasks on test day. You would report to the Test Day Supervisor. This is a flexible position in that you can simply sign up for the dates you are available to work.
Invigilators are proctors who supervise the test-takers, and may also assist with checking candidate ID, checking in candidate belongings, and escorting candidates to the restroom while the test is in progress. Duties will involve test day setup, using biometrics for ID checks, ensuring security of the test, clearly communicating instructions in English, and providing smooth running of operations with a smile. Invigilators must occasionally lift and or move up to 15 pounds.

Posting Details
I. DEPARTMENT INFORMATION
Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

To supervise an exam as a proctor, the individual must be willing to execute the following duties listed below:







out for tests and exams.

PART TIME JOB.
Join our test day administration team.
IELTS is the International English Language Testing System and is a global leader in standardized English language testing, used by thousands of universities around the world, as well as for immigration to various English-speaking countries. inlingua is a local language school and we are the largest IELTS Test Center in the USA and administer the test four times a month.
We are looking for Proctors (IELTS calls them "Invigilators") to assist with a wide variety of tasks on test day. You would report to the Test Day Supervisor. This is a flexible position in that you can simply sign up for the dates you are available to work.
Invigilators are proctors who supervise the test-takers, and may also assist with checking candidate ID, checking in candidate belongings, and escorting candidates to the restroom while the test is in progress. Duties will involve test day setup, using biometrics for ID checks, ensuring security of the test, clearly communicating instructions in English, and providing smooth running of operations with a smile. Invigilators must occasionally lift and or move up to 15 pounds.

I. DEPARTMENT INFORMATION
Job Description Summary:
Disability Support Services (DSS) at The George Washington University recognizes disability in the context of diversity. We work collaboratively with students, faculty and staff across the campus to foster a climate of universal academic excellence, while also promoting disability culture and GW’s broader diversity and inclusion initiatives. Reporting to the Senior Accessibility Associate, Test Proctoring, the DSS Test Proctor is responsible for overseeing testing, ensuring the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment during Finals Week 2022 (December 14th through December 22nd).

Test proctoring is testing overseen by an authorized, neutral proctor, who ensures the identity of the test taker and the integrity of the test taking environment. In short, a proctor is a proxy for the instructor, who oversees a test. At GW, testing accommodations are provided to students who have submitted the necessary documentation and have received a DSS Letter of Eligibility outlining their approved accommodations. Test Proctoring Services may be administered through DSS whenever students are unable to arrange to take their exams in class. As defined by the ADA, “testing accommodations are changes to the regular testing environment and auxiliary aids and services that allow individuals with disabilities to demonstrate their true aptitude or achievement level on standardized exams or other high-stakes tests.”

Title: Integration and Test Administrator

Mission Statement
Through the use of social and restorative justice principles, Five Keys provides traditionally underserved communities the opportunity to improve their lives through a focus on the Five Keys: EDUCATION, EMPLOYMENT, RECOVERY, FAMILY, COMMUNITY.
Five Keys Overview
Five Keys was founded in 2003 by the San Francisco Sheriffs Department as the first accredited charter high school in the nation to provide diploma programs for adults in county jails. Today we are a much different social justice non-profit agency that has expanded its charter schools into 9 counties, in 24 jail locations and over 80 community learning centers. In addition to our schools, now we also run multiple homeless shelters, employment programs, programs for the unsheltered, reentry programs and housing for women suffering from immense injustice.

The Course Proctor will provide management and oversight of courses being broadcast into campus locations virtually. The Course Proctor will prepare the classroom for the campus-based students to receive the course virtually at the receiving campus location by. This includes setting up the technology to receive the course virtually by following the manuals and instructions provided. This will require that the Course Proctor access the Learning Management System (Brightspace) and access the live video function within the course (Kaltura). The Course Proctor will ensure that the video and audio are functioning in the classroom prior to the course beginning and will remain in the class with the students throughout the duration of the class period. At the beginning of the class, the Course Proctor will record attendance for student participation at the local campus and will send to the corresponding instructor of record at the close of the class.
